******
[2] Kentucky
Date: Tue 26 Sep 2017
Source: Commonwealth Journal [edited]
http://tinyurl.com/y7a87mbe


A local veterinarian announced [Tue 26 Sep 2017] that Pulaski County has its 1st confirmed case of the season of West Nile virus in a horse.

However, the good news is as of Tuesday afternoon [26 Sep 2017], there have been no confirmed cases in humans within Pulaski or indeed the entire Lake Cumberland District, according to Lake Cumberland District Health Department Medical Director Christine Weyman. Weyman said that within Kentucky there have been 5 reported West Nile cases for humans this year [2017].

The disease, which is spread through mosquitoes, can affect horses, humans and some other types of animals like chickens, said Dr Bruce Burkett of Somerset Animal Hospital.

Burkett reported that a horse exhibiting signs was brought into his office by its owner a couple of weeks ago. Test results from the state lab came back Tuesday morning [26 Sep 2017] confirming the disease.

"We now know that mosquitoes in Pulaski County are carrying West Nile virus in high enough concentrations to infect a horse," Burkett said.

The horse in question is a 2-year-old Tennessee Walking Horse from eastern Pulaski that has never been vaccinated against the disease, he said.

"The horse is doing fine. It's responding to treatment and is recovering," he said, but he added that many horses do not respond. Horses are susceptible to contracting West Nile.

While there is no vaccination for the disease in humans, there is for horses, and Burkett said he would encourage farmers to get their horses vaccinated.

When the disease first hit the US in 1999, Burkett said several Kentucky cases for horses were reported, but shortly afterwards owners began vaccinating their livestock.

In the past few years, the number of cases has dropped, and some farmers either didn't get the booster shots for their horses or didn't vaccinate them at all, meaning the number of cases may rise again.

But beyond horses, Burkett showed concern for Pulaski's human residents, urging residents to take precautions.

While the majority of people infected by the virus show no symptoms or very mild symptoms, less than 1 percent will develop more serious symptoms including neurologic illnesses like, encephalitis or meningitis, according to the Centers for Disease Control.

As Burkett points out, however, "If that 1 percent is one of your family members, that number doesn't matter."

Symptoms for severe cases include headache, high fever, disorientation, coma, tremors, seizures or paralysis.

For horses, signs of a serious West Nile infection include fever, weakness or paralysis of hind limbs, aimless wandering, seizures, hyperexcitability and coma.

For humans and horses alike, the best way to prevent contracting the disease is to take precautions against mosquitoes and eliminate their breeding grounds.

Burkett suggested removing or avoiding standing water and mowing tall grass. For people, he suggested wearing long sleeves and using mosquito repellent while outside.

He added that the problem mosquitos will be around throughout the fall, until the 1st "hard freeze," and that he expected more equine cases to pop up among unvaccinated animals.

[Byline: Carla Slavey]

